 Navy to surround and bombard the hell out of them within the first few days of the invasion.... Our Air Force by 1941 was larger than both Japans and Germany's combined... Our Ability to rebuild military hardware exceeded Japan and Germany's combined by a huge factor... It certainly would've been drastically more costly to the US.. Germany's tanks would have been difficult to defend against... no argument there... as our tanks were so much smaller and less deadly... but our Air force was extremely effective in taking out german tanks.. even before we developed the p51<br><br>N. Africa was proof that our smaller tanks, against larger German forces, could win... Patton was no genius.. but he was effective... Rommel was a genius... and had alot of power to fight with... but the US prevailed against superior odds... against superior tanks<br><br>The US lost 130,000 troops fighting Germany... and killed 800,000 german troops... We lost half what the german's did in aircraft... we destroyed 3 tanks of theirs for every one of ours they destroyed... I think we did pretty good against Germany.. especially considering we did it on their turf.. the advantage goes to the defender...<br><br>Russia killed 1.4 million german troops... but they lost 13.1 million... best trained???? NOT... The russians were being pushed back and held at Stalingrad... but they werent able to hold it, until the US supplied them... once their troops had guns, they were able to stop the German advance, with the help of a second Winter... and the US invasion of Anzio... Once the US was in Europe on land... the Russians were able to rally, being that the Germans pulled 450,000 troops from the Russian Front to reinforce against the US, British and Canadian's push into Europe.<br><br>The US sat outside of Berlin, waiting for the Russian's to get there, so that per treaty, the Russian's could march into Berlin first... they sat there for 3 days, taking casualties so that the Russian Army could regai