br>Fortuitous. I'm not much for collecting things, but the one thing I do collect is old photos, particularly black and white photos from the first half of the nineteenth century. I keep them, or their reproductions, so as not to forget, if that makes sense to you.<br><br>One of my favorites is a picture taken just after the liberation of the Netherlands. The center of the photograph consists of two infantry officers, one American and one Englishman. They appear to be on the verge of complete exhaustion, and the shadows under their eyes suggest that they may not have slept in days. They are tired of fighting, tired of the war and all they want is to go home. Despite this, they are making their best efforts to smile for the photographer.<br><br>They are surrounded by Dutch workers. Healthy men, all of them, all of fighting age. They are not soldiers, however. They are miners.<br><br>The Dutch are pleased at this change in local governance,  and so they have donated some money to the Allied cause. Now they will mine for the Allies. The week before, they mined for the Nazis. <br><br>Ultimately, it makes little difference to them, for they'd rather be alive than righteous. Axis or Allies really doesn't matter, since they will survive regardless. Understandable, if not respectable.<br><br>This in no way diminishes the courage of the Dutch resistance or the vital intelligence they provided. Nor does it diminish the loss of your family members. It does, however, remind me of the value of friends, and of the value of allies.<br><br>The soldiers in that picture are not Dutch, nor are the Dutchmen in that picture soldiers. Looking at that photo, I am able to understand why Churchill originally intended NATO to have only two members.<br><br>No offense.<br><br><br>&quot;STOP SLAPPING YOURSELF ON YOUR SHOULDERS.&quot;<br><br>These are statements of fact, or at least statements quantifiable by academic discourse. If this upsets you, I suggest you restrict your